I responded to that element of Hernandez's post that was inaccurate. Why would I respond to the rest of it? I'm not going to criticize the fact that he says he suffers from PTSD, or that Vietnam may have spared us from a war in Nicaragua. The fact that he tossed that remark in so casually, taking it as a given, makes it much worse, and makes it scream out for a response all the more. It gets to the heart of the dispute between the vets and the protesters. He was implying that the protesters caused us to loose the war, which is outrageous. The only way we could have not lost the war is if we never fought it in the first place.<br><br>
Placing the protesters in two camps is an oversimplication. The ran the gamut in their views as the vets did. To focus on the question you raise, you could say that the leaders of our government were the bad guys because they sent American soldiers to their deaths, and the soldiers were the victims. You could also say that the soldiers were the bad guys since they killed so many Vietnamese, and the Vietnamese were the victims. However, it would be more accurate to say that the leaders of the American government were the bad guys because they were responsible for the deaths of both Americans and Vietnamese, American soldiers who wanted to be there because they wanted to kill Vietnamese were also bad guys, or perhaps both bad guys and victims since they were killed also, American soldiers who were drafted and did not want to be there were true victims, and the Vietnamese from both the North and South were both bad guys and victims. Yet this is an oversimplification also. Normally you would say that the soldiers who volunteered because they wanted to go over there and kill Vietnamese deserve no sympathy as opposed to those who were drafted who deserve sympathy. However, let's say someone is under the impression that the war was somehow an altruistic attempt to help the South Vietnamese, and they joined for that reason. Even thought they volunteered, we would have sympathy for them because they were misguided. Also, lets say someone joins, and while they are there, they change their mind, and decide that it's a bad war we shouldn't be involved in. They can't just walk up to their commanding officer and say that they've changed their mind, and they're leaving. On the other hand, if someone is joining the military during a war because they wish to fight in the war, they have a responsibility to find out about the war beforehand, to decide whether or not this is something worth fighting for.<br><br>
About the question as to why some vets were abused when they returned home, I think it's because they were viewed as a symbol of the military. Obviously people were against the military which lied about how successful the war was going, etc. The individual soldiers were not responsible for this but they became symbolic of the military. Also, when word got out about possible abuses committed by American soldiers, such as killing civilians, that increased hostility towards American soldiers, although very few were guilty of such things. If you really want to determine why some people abused vets, you have to dig deep into their psychology. Some people were terrified of being drafted. By lashing out against a soldier, which you do not want to become, you might convey to God, Fate, etc. how badly you don't want to become that person. By separating yourself from the soldiers as much as possible, you feel like you're somehow decreasing the likelihood of being drafted. A big reason why people lashed out against soldiers is because the military represents authority, and these people detested authority of any kind.<br><br>
From 1960 to 1970, Cambodia was ruled by King Norodom Suramarit, who was officially neutral in the Vietnam War. However, despite the neutrality, the North Vietnamese frequently entered Cambodia. They almost used Cambodia as a headquarters, where they stockpiled arms, etc., since they needn't fear an American attack in Cambodia. In March 1970, there was a coup d'etat in Cambodia, and General Lon Nol seized power. After the coup, the Cambodian government began trying to drive the North Vietnamese from their country. At this time, the Americans invaded Cambodia to fight the North Vietnamese there. Around that same time, the Cambodian rebel group the Khmer Rouge, became active in fighting Lon Nol's regime. In 1975, the Khmer Rouge took control of Cambodia and slaughtered three million people. In 1978, Vietnam invaded Cambodia, overthrew the Khmer Rouge, and ruled Cambodia through a puppet government. Nothing significant was occurring in Cambodia in October 1968. This was before the Cambodian government tried to evict the North Vietnamese from their country, and before the American invasion. This was before the Khmer Rouge became active since they rose up to fight the regime of Lon Nol after the coup. However, you have to understand that in this part of the world, you might see a village slaughtered even during the most peaceful periods. Since you're talking about only one village, it could have been done by almost anyone. My best guess would be the North Vietnamese. My second best guess would be the Khmer Rouge. However, it could have been done by almost anyone. Presumably, the Cambodian government was not involved since their rangers showed it to you. If the villagers were Hmong, that would provide a possible motivation. Perhaps someone just killed them because they were Hmong, out of ethnic hatred.<br><br>
I remember when I put the first post on this thread. Now I put the 103rd post. 
